result.execSummary:
The defendant James D Luedtke was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • OWI (4th w/in 5 yrs), a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(1)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes:
Court ordered defendant to pay a fine of $600 plus all mandatory costs, penalties, surcharges, and $50.00 ignition interlock surcharge, cash bail to apply. 
Pay all court costs, assessments and victim/witness surcharges. Provide a DNA sample for the Data Bank and pay all appropriate costs. The Court ordered that all court costs, fines, surcharges to be paid through collection by the Department of Corrections from 25% of funds under Sec. 973.05(4)(b) and as a condition of extended supervision.  Any amount remaining due and owing is subject to civil judgment.

Seek and maintain full-time employment.
Vocational training.
The defendant is advised as a convicted felon he may not carry or possess any firearms/body armor.
No driving without a valid driver's license and insurance.

Mental health assessment.
Court instructs the State to pursue felony failure to pay child support charges against the defendant. 
State must notify this court of any infractions by the defendant during the pendency of this sentence. 
The defendant is advised that voting rights are suspended during length of sentence.

ABSOLUTE SOBRIETY.
AODA and other counseling needs to be determined.

records.addlTxt:
Defendant James D Luedtke in court with attorney Bridget Joy Krause.  Defendant James D Luedtke in custody.  Michael Jerome Lonski appeared for the State of Wisconsin.    
The Court sentenced the defendant to serve a term of IMPRISONMENT of 6 YEARS in the Wisconsin State Prisons, with credit for 150 days time served.  CONFINEMENT of 3 YEARS and EXTENDED SUPERVISION of 3 YEARS.  The Court STAYED the sentence and placed the defendant on probation to the State Department of Corrections for a period of 3 YEARS.  Conditions of probation include:
-Serve 12 MONTHS in the House of Correction with Huber for counseling.
-The Court ordered that all court costs, fines, surcharges to be paid through collection by the Department of Corrections from 25% of funds under Sec. 973.05(4)(b) and as a condition of extended supervision.  Any amount remaining due and owing is subject to civil judgment.
-Pay all court costs, assessments and victim/witness surcharges.
-Provide a DNA sample for the Data Bank and pay all appropriate costs.
-ABSOLUTE SOBRIETY.
-AODA and other counseling needs to be determined.
-Seek and maintain full-time employment.
-No driving without a valid driver's license and insurance.
-Driver's safety plan.
-Mental health assessment.
-Vocational training.
The court may consider a day reporting center after 6 months.
Court instructs the State to pursue felony failure to pay child support charges against the defendant. 
State must notify this court of any infractions by the defendant during the pendency of this sentence. 
Court ordered defendant to pay a fine of $600 plus all mandatory costs, penalties, surcharges, and $50.00 ignition interlock surcharge, cash bail to apply.  Court ordered defendant's driving privileges revoked for a period of 36 months.    Court orders defendant restricted to operation of vehicles equipped with an ignition interlock device for 24 months to commence upon eligibility to reinstate license.  Notice of Right to Seek Postconviction Relief, Sentencing Referral Form and Pretrial Incarceration Credit received and filed.  
The defendant is advised as a convicted felon he may not carry or possess any firearms/body armor.
The defendant is advised that voting rights are suspended during length of sentence.
The defendant is not eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program.     
The defendant is not eligible for the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program.
Branch 21 is in jury trial and is unable to hear this matter.  Branch 38 will now hear this matter.  Parties notified, and case sent forthwith.

Defendant James D Luedtke in court with attorney Bridget Joy Krause.  Defendant James D Luedtke in custody.  Megan Patricia Carmody appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, plead GUILTY and was examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum received and filed.  Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis for the plea.  Defendant further advised that if he/she is not a US citizen deportation is possible.  Court found defendant guilty as charged in the Information and ordered entry of Judgment of Conviction.  Court ordered defendant REMANDED into the custody of the Sheriff's Department pending sentencing.  Sentencing hearing scheduled for July 6, 2015 at 01:30 pm.
